      <h2>Halogen Work Lights: The Dinosaur</h2>
      <p>Halogen work lights dominated job sites from the 1980s through the early 2010s. If you have one in your truck, you probably bought it before LED became affordable. Here's the honest truth about halogen in 2026:</p>

      <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cheapest upfront cost.</strong> You can find a 500W halogen tripod light for $20–$40. That's the only advantage.</li>
        <li><strong>Familiar warm color.</strong> Some old-school contractors prefer the warm 3000K color of halogen. It's not better for work — just familiar.</li>
        <li><strong>Simple, proven technology.</strong> No electronics to fail. When the bulb dies, you replace just the bulb.</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Terrible efficiency.</strong> 90% of the energy a halogen bulb consumes is turned into heat, not light. A 500W halogen produces about the same usable light as a 50W LED.</li>
        <li><strong>Dangerous heat.</strong> Halogen bulbs reach 400–600°F (200–315°C). They cause burns, melt plastic, and are a genuine fire hazard on dry job sites.</li>
        <li><strong>Short bulb life.</strong> 2,000–4,000 hours per bulb. On an active job site, you'll be replacing bulbs every few weeks. LED lasts 50,000 hours.</li>
        <li><strong>Fragile.</strong> Glass bulbs break when dropped. The thin wire filament breaks from vibration. A halogen light that gets knocked over is often done for the day.</li>
        <li><strong>Poor color for work.</strong> Warm 3000K light hides dirt and makes it harder to see details. Electricians struggle to distinguish wire colors under halogen.</li>
        <li><strong>Slow to re-strike.</strong> If a halogen bulb fails while hot (which happens), it can take minutes to cool down and restart.</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Verdict on Halogen:</strong> If you're still using halogen work lights, replace them. The energy savings from switching to LED typically pay for the new lights within 3–6 months of regular use. The safety improvement (no fire risk, no burns) alone is worth the upgrade.</p>

      <h2>Battery-Powered (Cordless) Work Lights: Maximum Flexibility</h2>
      <p>Battery-powered job site lights have improved dramatically in recent years. With high-capacity lithium-ion batteries and efficient LEDs, they can now run for hours on a single charge while producing useful amounts of light.</p>

      <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Zero cords.</strong> No extension cords to run, trip over, or blow breakers on. This is the #1 reason contractors buy battery lights — they work anywhere, instantly.</li>
        <li><strong>Battery ecosystem compatibility.</strong> If you already own DEWALT 20V tools (or Milwaukee M18, Makita 18V, etc.), a battery-powered light from the same platform shares batteries and chargers. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B077ZCTBFY?tag=sciencesolved-20" rel="nofollow sponsored" target="_blank">DEWALT DCL079B</a> (4.8★) runs on standard DEWALT 20V MAX batteries.</li>
        <li><strong>Perfect for remodels.</strong> When you're working in an occupied building or a space where power hasn't been roughed in, battery lights are the only practical option.</li>
        <li><strong>Quick setup/teardown.</strong> No cords to manage means you set up in seconds and move in seconds. Ideal for jobs where you're constantly relocating.</li>
        <li><strong>Emergency backup.</strong> Battery lights with motion sensors or automatic-on features work as emergency lighting during power failures.</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Limited runtime.</strong> Even with large batteries, runtime is measured in hours — not days. A 5Ah battery on the DEWALT DCL079B at full brightness gives roughly 2–4 hours. You need spare batteries and a charger on site.</li>
        <li><strong>Lower maximum brightness.</strong> Battery-powered lights typically max out at 3,000–5,000 lumens. Corded LED lights can reach 10,000–21,000+ lumens. You can't light a whole floor with a battery light.</li>
        <li><strong>Higher cost.</strong> The tool-only version is affordable, but you need batteries and chargers which add cost. The total system investment is higher than corded.</li>
        <li><strong>Battery degradation.</strong> Lithium batteries lose capacity over time. After 2–3 years of daily use, you may need new batteries to maintain runtime.</li>
        <li><strong>Platform lock-in.</strong> Once you buy into DEWALT 20V, you're invested. Switching platforms means replacing everything.</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Top Battery-Powered Pick:</strong></p>
      <ul>
