      </ul>

      <h2>Side-by-Side Comparison</h2>
      <div style="background:#1a2332;border:1px solid #2a3a4e;border-radius:0.5rem;padding:1.25rem;margin:1.5rem 0">
        <p><strong>Brightness per Watt:</strong></p>
        <p>LED Corded → 160–200 lm/W · LED Battery → 120–150 lm/W · Halogen → 15–20 lm/W</p>
        <p><strong>Typical Max Lumens:</strong></p>
        <p>LED Corded → 10,000–21,000 · LED Battery → 3,000–5,000 · Halogen → 2,000–5,000</p>
        <p><strong>Heat Output:</strong></p>
        <p>LED Corded → Low · LED Battery → Low · Halogen → Very High (fire risk)</p>
        <p><strong>Lifespan:</strong></p>
        <p>LED Corded → 50,000 hrs · LED Battery → 50,000 hrs (battery 500–1,000 cycles) · Halogen → 2,000 hrs</p>
        <p><strong>Upfront Cost:</strong></p>
        <p>LED Corded → $$ · LED Battery → $$$ (with batteries) · Halogen → $</p>
        <p><strong>Runtime (continuous):</strong></p>
        <p>LED Corded → Unlimited · LED Battery → 2–8 hrs (battery-dependent) · Halogen → Unlimited</p>
        <p><strong>Portability:</strong></p>
        <p>LED Corded → Cord-dependent · LED Battery → Maximum · Halogen → Cord-dependent</p>
        <p><strong>Weather Rating Options:</strong></p>
        <p>LED Corded → IP65–IP67 available · LED Battery → IP54–IP65 · Halogen → Rarely rated</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Decision Guide by Trade</h2>

      <h3>Electricians: LED Corded + Battery Combination</h3>
      <p>Electricians need true-color lighting for distinguishing wire colors (5000K LED) and flexibility for working in panels, crawlspaces, and occupied buildings. A DEWALT DCL079B (4.8★) battery light handles the no-power scenarios, while a 10000LM LED Work Light (4.6★) covers well-lit work areas. Avoid halogen entirely — the heat is a hazard around electrical panels and the color rendering is inadequate for distinguishing black/red/blue wires.</p>

      <h3>Framers & Carpenters: LED Corded Primary</h3>
      <p>Framers work in large spaces that need bright, even light. The Zetunlo 21000L Tripod Light (4.6★) or the 2-Pack 50W LEDs (4.8★) provide the necessary output. Battery lights don't have enough runtime or brightness for framing work. Power is usually available at this stage of construction.</p>

      <h3>Remodelers & Finish Crews: Battery Lights</h3>
      <p>Remodels are where battery lights shine — power is often limited, and you're moving from room to room. The DEWALT DCL079B (4.8★) is ideal. Add a HYPERLITE 50FT String Light (4.6★) for hallways and rooms where you need ambient coverage.</p>

      <h3>Concrete & Masonry Workers: Corded LED with IP66</h3>
      <p>Wet environments demand IP66-rated lights. The 10000LM LED Work Light (4.6★) and the Zetunlo 21000L Tripod Light (4.6★) are both IP66. Avoid battery lights — the concrete dust and moisture will degrade connections. Halogen is too hot and fragile for concrete work.</p>

      <h3>Plumbers & HVAC: Mixed — Corded for Big Areas, Battery for Tight Spots</h3>
      <p>For mechanical rooms and large equipment areas, the 2-Pack 50W LEDs (4.8★) provide excellent coverage. For crawlspaces, attics, and tight mechanical chases, the DEWALT DCL079B (4.8★) or any portable battery light gives you light where there's no room for cords.</p>

      <h2>Cost Comparison: Total Cost of Ownership</h2>
      <p>Let's run the numbers for a contractor running two lights for 8 hours per day, 5 days per week, over one year:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Halogen (2 × 500W):</strong> 8,000 hours × 1,000W total = 8,000 kWh. At $0.12/kWh = <strong>$960/year in electricity</strong>. Plus 2–4 bulb replacements × $5 = $10–$20. Total: ~$980.</li>
        <li><strong>LED Corded (2 × 50W):</strong> 8,000 hours × 100W total = 800 kWh. At $0.12/kWh = <strong>$96/year in electricity</strong>. Zero bulb replacements. Total: ~$96 + light cost (~$60).</li>
        <li><strong>LED Battery (DEWALT DCL079B + 2 batteries):</strong> Zero electricity cost on the job site (charging at home/shop adds minimal cost). <strong>$0/year electricity</strong>. But battery replacement every 2–3 years adds ~$100–$200.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Halogen costs roughly <strong>10x more in electricity</strong> than LED to run. The LED lights pay for themselves in energy savings within 2–3 months.</p>

      <h2>Final Recommendation</h2>
      <p>For the vast majority of construction trades, the smartest investment is a combination approach:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>2–4 corded LED lights</strong> (10000LM or 2-Pack 50W) for your primary area lighting — these give you unlimited runtime at maximum brightness for the lowest operating cost.</li>
        <li><strong>1 battery-powered LED light</strong> (DEWALT DCL079B or equivalent) for remodels, no-power scenarios, and quick patchwork.</li>
        <li><strong>String lights</strong> (100FT or 50FT) for hallways, basements, and buildings where even ambient coverage is needed.</li>
        <li><strong>Zero halogen lights</strong> — there is no scenario in 2026 where a new halogen work light purchase makes sense over an LED alternative.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The technology decision is clear: LED is superior in every metric that matters on a job site. The only real question is whether you need corded (unlimited brightness/runtime) or battery (maximum portability/flexibility). For most contractors, the answer is both.</p>

